        {
          "ruleId": "WSTG-ATHZ-03",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "DVWA's security level (low/medium/high/impossible) is stored in a client-controlled cookie named \"security\" rather than server-side session state. Any authenticated user can freely modify this cookie value to change the application's security posture without server-side validation. This means:\n1. An admin who sets security=high (intending to restrict exploitation) can have their setting overridden by any authenticated user simply setting security=low in their browser.\n2. The security cookie is trusted entirely client-side \u2014 the server applies whichever level the client presents.\n\nProof: With the same valid session (PHPSESSID), changing the security cookie from \"low\" to \"high\" changes which SQL injection code path executes. Setting it back to \"low\" immediately re-enables the vulnerable code path, confirming the server applies no independent server-side security level per session.\n\nThis means all security hardening intended by the administrator can be trivially bypassed by any authenticated user, rendering the \"high\" and \"impossible\" security levels ineffective as access controls."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "http://ec2-18-188-101-84.us-east-2.compute.amazonaws.com/security.php"
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "clementine/v1": "WSTG-ATHZ-03:http://ec2-18-188-101-84.us-east-2.compute.amazonaws.com/security.php"
          },
          "fixes": [
            {
              "description": {
                "text": "Store the security level in server-side session state rather than a client-controlled cookie. The security level should be set once by an administrator and stored in the PHP session ($_SESSION['security']), not read from $_COOKIE['security'] on each request. Users should not be able to influence their own security level."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "WSTG-SESS-03",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "DVWA does not issue a new session identifier upon successful user authentication. The PHPSESSID assigned before login remains unchanged after the user authenticates, enabling session fixation attacks. An attacker who can fix a victim's session token (e.g., via a URL parameter if trans_sid were enabled, or via subdomain cookie injection) would be able to hijack the authenticated session without knowing the victim's credentials.\n\nEvidence: Pre-login PHPSESSID `0hd80hcaic4514t1kcbm1q32f2` remained identical post-login (cookie jar comparison). The server issued a 302 redirect to index.php on successful login but did NOT issue a new Set-Cookie: PHPSESSID header, confirming the session ID was reused."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "http://ec2-18-188-101-84.us-east-2.compute.amazonaws.com/login.php"
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "clementine/v1": "WSTG-SESS-03:http://ec2-18-188-101-84.us-east-2.compute.amazonaws.com/login.php"
          },
          "fixes": [
            {
              "description": {
                "text": "Call session_regenerate_id(true) immediately after successful authentication in login.php. The 'true' parameter deletes the old session file. Example: if (valid_credentials) { session_regenerate_id(true); $_SESSION['user'] = $username; }"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
